& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Coronary artery interventions and surgical procedures are used in the treatment of coronary artery disease and some congenital heart diseases. Cardiac and noncardiac complications can occur at variable times after these procedures, with the clinical presentation ranging from asymptomatic to devastating symptoms. Invasive coronary angiography is the reference standard modality used in the evaluation of coronary arteries, with intravascular US and optical coherence tomography providing high-resolution information regarding the vessel wall. CT is the mostly commonly used noninvasive imaging modality in the evaluation of coronary artery intervention complications and allows assessment of the stent, lumen of the stent, lumen of the coronary arteries, and extracoronary structures. MRI is limited to the evaluation of the proximal coronary arteries but allows comprehensive evaluation of the myocardium, including ischemia and infarction. The authors review the clinical symptoms and pathophysiologic and imaging features of various complications of coronary artery interventions and surgical procedures. Complications of percutaneous coronary interventions are discussed, including restenosis, thrombosis, dissection of coronary arteries or the aorta, coronary wall rupture or perforation, stent deployment failure, stent fracture, stent infection, stent migration or embolism, and reperfusion injury. Complications of several surgical procedures are reviewed, including coronary artery bypass grafting, coronary artery reimplantation procedure (for anomalous origin from opposite sinuses or the pulmonary artery or as part of surgical procedures such as arterial switching surgery and the Bentall and Cabrol procedures), coronary artery unroofing, and the Takeuchi procedure.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200147">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200147">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary complications of ICA in two patients. (a) Curved planar reconstruction image and corresponding cross-sectional CTA image (inset) in a 42-year-old woman after ICA show a coronary dissection (arrows) from the left main coronary artery to the middle of the left anterior descending (LAD) artery. (b, c) Axial maximum intensity projection CT image (b) in a 70-year-old man after he underwent ICA shows a focal pseudoaneurysm with a focal outpouching of iodinated contrast material (curved arrow), which is adjacent to the right coronary artery (RCA) and sinoatrial nodal artery and the surrounding hematoma (straight arrow in b). ICA image (c) shows the focal outpouching of contrast material (curved arrow) adjacent to the proximal RCA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig1a.jpeg" height="1414" width="1414" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Coronary complications of ICA in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Curved planar reconstruction image and corresponding cross-sectional CTA image (inset) in a 42-year-old woman after ICA show a coronary dissection (arrows) from the left main coronary artery to the middle of the left anterior descending (LAD) artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection CT image <b>(b)</b> in a 70-year-old man after he underwent ICA shows a focal pseudoaneurysm with a focal outpouching of iodinated contrast material (curved arrow), which is adjacent to the right coronary artery (RCA) and sinoatrial nodal artery and the surrounding hematoma (straight arrow in <b>b</b>). ICA image <b>(c)</b> shows the focal outpouching of contrast material (curved arrow) adjacent to the proximal RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary complications of ICA in two patients. (a) Curved planar reconstruction image and corresponding cross-sectional CTA image (inset) in a 42-year-old woman after ICA show a coronary dissection (arrows) from the left main coronary artery to the middle of the left anterior descending (LAD) artery. (b, c) Axial maximum intensity projection CT image (b) in a 70-year-old man after he underwent ICA shows a focal pseudoaneurysm with a focal outpouching of iodinated contrast material (curved arrow), which is adjacent to the right coronary artery (RCA) and sinoatrial nodal artery and the surrounding hematoma (straight arrow in b). ICA image (c) shows the focal outpouching of contrast material (curved arrow) adjacent to the proximal RCA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig1b.jpeg" height="1414" width="901" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Coronary complications of ICA in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Curved planar reconstruction image and corresponding cross-sectional CTA image (inset) in a 42-year-old woman after ICA show a coronary dissection (arrows) from the left main coronary artery to the middle of the left anterior descending (LAD) artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection CT image <b>(b)</b> in a 70-year-old man after he underwent ICA shows a focal pseudoaneurysm with a focal outpouching of iodinated contrast material (curved arrow), which is adjacent to the right coronary artery (RCA) and sinoatrial nodal artery and the surrounding hematoma (straight arrow in <b>b</b>). ICA image <b>(c)</b> shows the focal outpouching of contrast material (curved arrow) adjacent to the proximal RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary complications of ICA in two patients. (a) Curved planar reconstruction image and corresponding cross-sectional CTA image (inset) in a 42-year-old woman after ICA show a coronary dissection (arrows) from the left main coronary artery to the middle of the left anterior descending (LAD) artery. (b, c) Axial maximum intensity projection CT image (b) in a 70-year-old man after he underwent ICA shows a focal pseudoaneurysm with a focal outpouching of iodinated contrast material (curved arrow), which is adjacent to the right coronary artery (RCA) and sinoatrial nodal artery and the surrounding hematoma (straight arrow in b). ICA image (c) shows the focal outpouching of contrast material (curved arrow) adjacent to the proximal RCA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig1c.jpeg" height="1414" width="1385" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Coronary complications of ICA in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Curved planar reconstruction image and corresponding cross-sectional CTA image (inset) in a 42-year-old woman after ICA show a coronary dissection (arrows) from the left main coronary artery to the middle of the left anterior descending (LAD) artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection CT image <b>(b)</b> in a 70-year-old man after he underwent ICA shows a focal pseudoaneurysm with a focal outpouching of iodinated contrast material (curved arrow), which is adjacent to the right coronary artery (RCA) and sinoatrial nodal artery and the surrounding hematoma (straight arrow in <b>b</b>). ICA image <b>(c)</b> shows the focal outpouching of contrast material (curved arrow) adjacent to the proximal RCA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Aortic dissection in a 68-year-old man. Axial CTA image acquired after ICA for the evaluation of CABG patency shows a focal dissection (straight arrow) of the ascending aorta, with a partially thrombosed false lumen. The CABG is seen in cross-section (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig2.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Aortic dissection in a 68-year-old man. Axial CTA image acquired after ICA for the evaluation of CABG patency shows a focal dissection (straight arrow) of the ascending aorta, with a partially thrombosed false lumen. The CABG is seen in cross-section (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="Type A aortic dissection as a complication of coronary intervention in a 57-year-old man. Axial noncontrast (a) and coronal contrast-enhanced (b) CT images show a type A aortic dissection with highly attenuating contrast material from a previous ICA procedure in the false lumen of the ascending and descending aorta (straight arrows). The pericardium also shows high attenuation because of pericardial hemorrhage (curved arrows), indicating a rupture into the pericardium."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig3a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Type A aortic dissection as a complication of coronary intervention in a 57-year-old man. Axial noncontrast <b>(a)</b> and coronal contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> CT images show a type A aortic dissection with highly attenuating contrast material from a previous ICA procedure in the false lumen of the ascending and descending aorta (straight arrows). The pericardium also shows high attenuation because of pericardial hemorrhage (curved arrows), indicating a rupture into the pericardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Type A aortic dissection as a complication of coronary intervention in a 57-year-old man. Axial noncontrast (a) and coronal contrast-enhanced (b) CT images show a type A aortic dissection with highly attenuating contrast material from a previous ICA procedure in the false lumen of the ascending and descending aorta (straight arrows). The pericardium also shows high attenuation because of pericardial hemorrhage (curved arrows), indicating a rupture into the pericardium."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig3b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Type A aortic dissection as a complication of coronary intervention in a 57-year-old man. Axial noncontrast <b>(a)</b> and coronal contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> CT images show a type A aortic dissection with highly attenuating contrast material from a previous ICA procedure in the false lumen of the ascending and descending aorta (straight arrows). The pericardium also shows high attenuation because of pericardial hemorrhage (curved arrows), indicating a rupture into the pericardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="Rupture of the RCA as a complication of coronary angioplasty in a 66-year-old man. (a) ICA image shows extravasation of contrast media from the proximal RCA (arrow). (b) Sagittal CTA image shows rupture of the RCA (curved arrow), with hyperattenuating contrast media in the pericardial space (straight arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig4a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Rupture of the RCA as a complication of coronary angioplasty in a 66-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> ICA image shows extravasation of contrast media from the proximal RCA (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CTA image shows rupture of the RCA (curved arrow), with hyperattenuating contrast media in the pericardial space (straight arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Rupture of the RCA as a complication of coronary angioplasty in a 66-year-old man. (a) ICA image shows extravasation of contrast media from the proximal RCA (arrow). (b) Sagittal CTA image shows rupture of the RCA (curved arrow), with hyperattenuating contrast media in the pericardial space (straight arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig4b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Rupture of the RCA as a complication of coronary angioplasty in a 66-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> ICA image shows extravasation of contrast media from the proximal RCA (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CTA image shows rupture of the RCA (curved arrow), with hyperattenuating contrast media in the pericardial space (straight arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="ISR in a 72-year-old man. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image shows a stent in the distal RCA with focal luminal hypoattenuation that is causing mild stenosis (arrow). Cross-sectional inset image (upper right) at the level of stenosis shows stenosis of less than 50%, which is mild stenosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig5.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. ISR in a 72-year-old man. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image shows a stent in the distal RCA with focal luminal hypoattenuation that is causing mild stenosis (arrow). Cross-sectional inset image (upper right) at the level of stenosis shows stenosis of less than 50%, which is mild stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal CT appearance of coronary stents in a 64-year-old woman. Curved multiplanar CTA image shows stents in the proximal, middle, and distal segments of the RCA, with a homogeneous lumen (arrows). No thrombus or restenosis is seen."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig6.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Normal CT appearance of coronary stents in a 64-year-old woman. Curved multiplanar CTA image shows stents in the proximal, middle, and distal segments of the RCA, with a homogeneous lumen (arrows). No thrombus or restenosis is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="CT techniques for improving visualization of the stent lumen. CT images show widening of window widths (left), the use of sharper kernel filters for higher spatial resolution (middle), and the use of an iterative reconstruction algorithm for noise reduction (right)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig7.jpeg" height="1894" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. CT techniques for improving visualization of the stent lumen. CT images show widening of window widths (left), the use of sharper kernel filters for higher spatial resolution (middle), and the use of an iterative reconstruction algorithm for noise reduction (right).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="Stent thrombosis in a 73-year-old woman. (a) Curved planar reconstruction CTA image shows complete occlusion in the distal left circumflex artery stent due to a thrombus (straight arrow). Note the complete occlusion in the distal left circumflex artery and the obtuse marginal branch (curved arrow). (b) Cinematic rendering technique image shows the location of the coronary stent (straight arrow) and a complete absence of contrast material in the distal left circumflex artery and the obtuse marginal branch (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig8a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Stent thrombosis in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Curved planar reconstruction CTA image shows complete occlusion in the distal left circumflex artery stent due to a thrombus (straight arrow). Note the complete occlusion in the distal left circumflex artery and the obtuse marginal branch (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Cinematic rendering technique image shows the location of the coronary stent (straight arrow) and a complete absence of contrast material in the distal left circumflex artery and the obtuse marginal branch (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="Stent thrombosis in a 73-year-old woman. (a) Curved planar reconstruction CTA image shows complete occlusion in the distal left circumflex artery stent due to a thrombus (straight arrow). Note the complete occlusion in the distal left circumflex artery and the obtuse marginal branch (curved arrow). (b) Cinematic rendering technique image shows the location of the coronary stent (straight arrow) and a complete absence of contrast material in the distal left circumflex artery and the obtuse marginal branch (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig8b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Stent thrombosis in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Curved planar reconstruction CTA image shows complete occlusion in the distal left circumflex artery stent due to a thrombus (straight arrow). Note the complete occlusion in the distal left circumflex artery and the obtuse marginal branch (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> Cinematic rendering technique image shows the location of the coronary stent (straight arrow) and a complete absence of contrast material in the distal left circumflex artery and the obtuse marginal branch (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="Stent deployment failure in a 58-year-old woman with persistent chest pain after recent PCI. Cinematic rendering technique image (a) and curved planar reconstruction CTA image (b) show stents in both branches of a duplicated LAD artery (arrows in a). The stent in the left LAD artery is located in an abnormal proximal position and is causing flow obstruction to the right branch (black arrow in b). In-stent filling defects suggestive of early thrombosis (curved arrow in b) are seen. The proximal stent was retrieved and a different stent was placed."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig9a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Stent deployment failure in a 58-year-old woman with persistent chest pain after recent PCI. Cinematic rendering technique image <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction CTA image <b>(b)</b> show stents in both branches of a duplicated LAD artery (arrows in <b>a</b>). The stent in the left LAD artery is located in an abnormal proximal position and is causing flow obstruction to the right branch (black arrow in <b>b</b>). In-stent filling defects suggestive of early thrombosis (curved arrow in <b>b</b>) are seen. The proximal stent was retrieved and a different stent was placed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="Stent deployment failure in a 58-year-old woman with persistent chest pain after recent PCI. Cinematic rendering technique image (a) and curved planar reconstruction CTA image (b) show stents in both branches of a duplicated LAD artery (arrows in a). The stent in the left LAD artery is located in an abnormal proximal position and is causing flow obstruction to the right branch (black arrow in b). In-stent filling defects suggestive of early thrombosis (curved arrow in b) are seen. The proximal stent was retrieved and a different stent was placed."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig9b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Stent deployment failure in a 58-year-old woman with persistent chest pain after recent PCI. Cinematic rendering technique image <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction CTA image <b>(b)</b> show stents in both branches of a duplicated LAD artery (arrows in <b>a</b>). The stent in the left LAD artery is located in an abnormal proximal position and is causing flow obstruction to the right branch (black arrow in <b>b</b>). In-stent filling defects suggestive of early thrombosis (curved arrow in <b>b</b>) are seen. The proximal stent was retrieved and a different stent was placed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic" aria-label="Stent deployment failure in an 81-year-old woman. Cinematic rendering technique (a) and curved planar reconstruction (b) CTA images show an unexpanded stent in the left main and proximal LAD artery (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig10a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Stent deployment failure in an 81-year-old woman. Cinematic rendering technique <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction <b>(b)</b> CTA images show an unexpanded stent in the left main and proximal LAD artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="Stent deployment failure in an 81-year-old woman. Cinematic rendering technique (a) and curved planar reconstruction (b) CTA images show an unexpanded stent in the left main and proximal LAD artery (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig10b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Stent deployment failure in an 81-year-old woman. Cinematic rendering technique <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction <b>(b)</b> CTA images show an unexpanded stent in the left main and proximal LAD artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Stent fracture in a 59-year-old man. Sagittal multiplanar reconstruction CT image and corresponding cross-sectional CTA image (inset) show focal discontinuity of the stent wall in the middle RCA, which is consistent with a stent fracture (straight arrows). Extravasation of contrast material through the rupture, with a small collection of it adjacent to the stent (curved arrows), is also seen."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig11.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Stent fracture in a 59-year-old man. Sagittal multiplanar reconstruction CT image and corresponding cross-sectional CTA image (inset) show focal discontinuity of the stent wall in the middle RCA, which is consistent with a stent fracture (straight arrows). Extravasation of contrast material through the rupture, with a small collection of it adjacent to the stent (curved arrows), is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary artery dissection after PCI in a 54-year-old man. Volume-rendered technique reconstruction (a) and curved planar reconstruction (b) CTA images show focal circumferential coronary artery dissection in the ostium (arrow) of the RCA, proximal to a stent. Although this finding appears similar to a pseudoaneurysm on the curved planar reconstruction CTA image, it is circumferential, which is shown with the use of the three-dimensional technique, indicating that it is a dissection."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig12a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Coronary artery dissection after PCI in a 54-year-old man. Volume-rendered technique reconstruction <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction <b>(b)</b> CTA images show focal circumferential coronary artery dissection in the ostium (arrow) of the RCA, proximal to a stent. Although this finding appears similar to a pseudoaneurysm on the curved planar reconstruction CTA image, it is circumferential, which is shown with the use of the three-dimensional technique, indicating that it is a dissection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary artery dissection after PCI in a 54-year-old man. Volume-rendered technique reconstruction (a) and curved planar reconstruction (b) CTA images show focal circumferential coronary artery dissection in the ostium (arrow) of the RCA, proximal to a stent. Although this finding appears similar to a pseudoaneurysm on the curved planar reconstruction CTA image, it is circumferential, which is shown with the use of the three-dimensional technique, indicating that it is a dissection."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig12b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Coronary artery dissection after PCI in a 54-year-old man. Volume-rendered technique reconstruction <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction <b>(b)</b> CTA images show focal circumferential coronary artery dissection in the ostium (arrow) of the RCA, proximal to a stent. Although this finding appears similar to a pseudoaneurysm on the curved planar reconstruction CTA image, it is circumferential, which is shown with the use of the three-dimensional technique, indicating that it is a dissection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary wall rupture in a 56-year-old man. Two-chamber multiplanar (a) and axial oblique maximum intensity projection (b) CTA images show a curved stent in the epicardial space that is outside the course of the LAD artery (straight arrow). There is a large adjacent epicardial collection of fluid, which is consistent with a hematoma (curved arrow in a), with mass effect over the anterior wall of the left ventricle."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig13a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Coronary wall rupture in a 56-year-old man. Two-chamber multiplanar <b>(a)</b> and axial oblique maximum intensity projection <b>(b)</b> CTA images show a curved stent in the epicardial space that is outside the course of the LAD artery (straight arrow). There is a large adjacent epicardial collection of fluid, which is consistent with a hematoma (curved arrow in <b>a</b>), with mass effect over the anterior wall of the left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary wall rupture in a 56-year-old man. Two-chamber multiplanar (a) and axial oblique maximum intensity projection (b) CTA images show a curved stent in the epicardial space that is outside the course of the LAD artery (straight arrow). There is a large adjacent epicardial collection of fluid, which is consistent with a hematoma (curved arrow in a), with mass effect over the anterior wall of the left ventricle."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig13b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Coronary wall rupture in a 56-year-old man. Two-chamber multiplanar <b>(a)</b> and axial oblique maximum intensity projection <b>(b)</b> CTA images show a curved stent in the epicardial space that is outside the course of the LAD artery (straight arrow). There is a large adjacent epicardial collection of fluid, which is consistent with a hematoma (curved arrow in <b>a</b>), with mass effect over the anterior wall of the left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="Reperfusion injury after PCI in a 33-year-old man who underwent successful thrombectomy in a severely stenotic diagonal artery. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted MR image shows an area of edema as high signal intensity in the anterior wall and central lower signal intensity (arrow). (b) Short-axis contrast-enhanced inversion-recovery gradient-recalled-echo MR image shows corresponding nonenhancement that is surrounded by intense delayed enhancement (arrow), which is indicative of hemorrhagic microvascular obstruction. (c) Short-axis T2-weighted map also shows the abnormal low signal intensity of this lesion (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig14a.jpeg" height="1500" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Reperfusion injury after PCI in a 33-year-old man who underwent successful thrombectomy in a severely stenotic diagonal artery. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted MR image shows an area of edema as high signal intensity in the anterior wall and central lower signal intensity (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis contrast-enhanced inversion-recovery gradient-recalled-echo MR image shows corresponding nonenhancement that is surrounded by intense delayed enhancement (arrow), which is indicative of hemorrhagic microvascular obstruction. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted map also shows the abnormal low signal intensity of this lesion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Reperfusion injury after PCI in a 33-year-old man who underwent successful thrombectomy in a severely stenotic diagonal artery. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted MR image shows an area of edema as high signal intensity in the anterior wall and central lower signal intensity (arrow). (b) Short-axis contrast-enhanced inversion-recovery gradient-recalled-echo MR image shows corresponding nonenhancement that is surrounded by intense delayed enhancement (arrow), which is indicative of hemorrhagic microvascular obstruction. (c) Short-axis T2-weighted map also shows the abnormal low signal intensity of this lesion (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig14b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Reperfusion injury after PCI in a 33-year-old man who underwent successful thrombectomy in a severely stenotic diagonal artery. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted MR image shows an area of edema as high signal intensity in the anterior wall and central lower signal intensity (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis contrast-enhanced inversion-recovery gradient-recalled-echo MR image shows corresponding nonenhancement that is surrounded by intense delayed enhancement (arrow), which is indicative of hemorrhagic microvascular obstruction. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted map also shows the abnormal low signal intensity of this lesion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic" aria-label="Reperfusion injury after PCI in a 33-year-old man who underwent successful thrombectomy in a severely stenotic diagonal artery. (a) Short-axis T2-weighted MR image shows an area of edema as high signal intensity in the anterior wall and central lower signal intensity (arrow). (b) Short-axis contrast-enhanced inversion-recovery gradient-recalled-echo MR image shows corresponding nonenhancement that is surrounded by intense delayed enhancement (arrow), which is indicative of hemorrhagic microvascular obstruction. (c) Short-axis T2-weighted map also shows the abnormal low signal intensity of this lesion (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig14c.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Reperfusion injury after PCI in a 33-year-old man who underwent successful thrombectomy in a severely stenotic diagonal artery. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted MR image shows an area of edema as high signal intensity in the anterior wall and central lower signal intensity (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis contrast-enhanced inversion-recovery gradient-recalled-echo MR image shows corresponding nonenhancement that is surrounded by intense delayed enhancement (arrow), which is indicative of hemorrhagic microvascular obstruction. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted map also shows the abnormal low signal intensity of this lesion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic" aria-label="Reperfusion injury after PCI in a 63-year-old man with an ST-elevation myocardial infarction and RCA occlusion who had two drug-eluting stents placed in the RCA, with restoration of TIMI 2 flow. In the immediate postsurgical period, he developed shock hemodynamics. Reformatted four-chamber (a) and short-axis (b) CT images show a ventricular intramyocardial dissection (arrow), which is a form of incomplete rupture."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig15a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Reperfusion injury after PCI in a 63-year-old man with an ST-elevation myocardial infarction and RCA occlusion who had two drug-eluting stents placed in the RCA, with restoration of TIMI 2 flow. In the immediate postsurgical period, he developed shock hemodynamics. Reformatted four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> CT images show a ventricular intramyocardial dissection (arrow), which is a form of incomplete rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="Reperfusion injury after PCI in a 63-year-old man with an ST-elevation myocardial infarction and RCA occlusion who had two drug-eluting stents placed in the RCA, with restoration of TIMI 2 flow. In the immediate postsurgical period, he developed shock hemodynamics. Reformatted four-chamber (a) and short-axis (b) CT images show a ventricular intramyocardial dissection (arrow), which is a form of incomplete rupture."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig15b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Reperfusion injury after PCI in a 63-year-old man with an ST-elevation myocardial infarction and RCA occlusion who had two drug-eluting stents placed in the RCA, with restoration of TIMI 2 flow. In the immediate postsurgical period, he developed shock hemodynamics. Reformatted four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> CT images show a ventricular intramyocardial dissection (arrow), which is a form of incomplete rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic" aria-label="Spasm of a radial artery graft in a 71-year-old man. (a) Volume-rendered technique CTA image shows diffuse narrowing of a radial artery graft (arrows) to the patent ductus arteriosus, without discrete focal stenosis. (b) ICA image shows diffuse narrowing of the radial bypass graft (arrows) due to vasospasm."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig16a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Spasm of a radial artery graft in a 71-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered technique CTA image shows diffuse narrowing of a radial artery graft (arrows) to the patent ductus arteriosus, without discrete focal stenosis. <b>(b)</b> ICA image shows diffuse narrowing of the radial bypass graft (arrows) due to vasospasm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Spasm of a radial artery graft in a 71-year-old man. (a) Volume-rendered technique CTA image shows diffuse narrowing of a radial artery graft (arrows) to the patent ductus arteriosus, without discrete focal stenosis. (b) ICA image shows diffuse narrowing of the radial bypass graft (arrows) due to vasospasm."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig16b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Spasm of a radial artery graft in a 71-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered technique CTA image shows diffuse narrowing of a radial artery graft (arrows) to the patent ductus arteriosus, without discrete focal stenosis. <b>(b)</b> ICA image shows diffuse narrowing of the radial bypass graft (arrows) due to vasospasm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary bypass graft thrombosis in a 65-year-old man. Cinematic rendering technique image (a) and curved planar reconstruction CTA image (b) show a patent left internal mammary artery (LIMA)–LAD artery graft (curved arrow) and two completely occluded venous grafts (VG) to the obtuse marginal (OM) and posterior descending arteries (PDA) due to thrombosis (straight arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig17a.jpeg" height="1557" width="1093" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Coronary bypass graft thrombosis in a 65-year-old man. Cinematic rendering technique image <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction CTA image <b>(b)</b> show a patent left internal mammary artery <i>(LIMA)–</i>LAD artery graft (curved arrow) and two completely occluded venous grafts <i>(VG)</i> to the obtuse marginal <i>(OM)</i> and posterior descending arteries <i>(PDA)</i> due to thrombosis (straight arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary bypass graft thrombosis in a 65-year-old man. Cinematic rendering technique image (a) and curved planar reconstruction CTA image (b) show a patent left internal mammary artery (LIMA)–LAD artery graft (curved arrow) and two completely occluded venous grafts (VG) to the obtuse marginal (OM) and posterior descending arteries (PDA) due to thrombosis (straight arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig17b.jpeg" height="1557" width="1557" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Coronary bypass graft thrombosis in a 65-year-old man. Cinematic rendering technique image <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction CTA image <b>(b)</b> show a patent left internal mammary artery <i>(LIMA)–</i>LAD artery graft (curved arrow) and two completely occluded venous grafts <i>(VG)</i> to the obtuse marginal <i>(OM)</i> and posterior descending arteries <i>(PDA)</i> due to thrombosis (straight arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic" aria-label="CABG stenosis in a 78-year-old man. Cinematic rendering technique (a) and curved planar reconstruction (b) CTA images illustrate severe stenosis in the distal anastomosis of a venous graft to the obtuse marginal branch (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig18a.jpeg" height="1319" width="1309" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. CABG stenosis in a 78-year-old man. Cinematic rendering technique <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction <b>(b)</b> CTA images illustrate severe stenosis in the distal anastomosis of a venous graft to the obtuse marginal branch (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic" aria-label="CABG stenosis in a 78-year-old man. Cinematic rendering technique (a) and curved planar reconstruction (b) CTA images illustrate severe stenosis in the distal anastomosis of a venous graft to the obtuse marginal branch (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig18b.jpeg" height="1320" width="1341" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. CABG stenosis in a 78-year-old man. Cinematic rendering technique <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction <b>(b)</b> CTA images illustrate severe stenosis in the distal anastomosis of a venous graft to the obtuse marginal branch (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic" aria-label="Occlusion of a CABG in a 61-year-old man. (a) Cinematic rendering technique CTA image shows two occluded CABGs: a left internal mammary artery to ramus intermedius (curved arrow) graft, and a right internal mammary artery to LAD artery (straight arrow) graft in a “Y” anastomosis with the left internal mammary artery. (b) Curved planar reconstruction CT image shows complete occlusion of the left internal mammary artery graft (straight arrow) to the ramus intermedius (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig19a.jpeg" height="1467" width="1183" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Occlusion of a CABG in a 61-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Cinematic rendering technique CTA image shows two occluded CABGs: a left internal mammary artery to ramus intermedius (curved arrow) graft, and a right internal mammary artery to LAD artery (straight arrow) graft in a “Y” anastomosis with the left internal mammary artery. <b>(b)</b> Curved planar reconstruction CT image shows complete occlusion of the left internal mammary artery graft (straight arrow) to the ramus intermedius (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic" aria-label="Occlusion of a CABG in a 61-year-old man. (a) Cinematic rendering technique CTA image shows two occluded CABGs: a left internal mammary artery to ramus intermedius (curved arrow) graft, and a right internal mammary artery to LAD artery (straight arrow) graft in a “Y” anastomosis with the left internal mammary artery. (b) Curved planar reconstruction CT image shows complete occlusion of the left internal mammary artery graft (straight arrow) to the ramus intermedius (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig19b.jpeg" height="1467" width="1467" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Occlusion of a CABG in a 61-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Cinematic rendering technique CTA image shows two occluded CABGs: a left internal mammary artery to ramus intermedius (curved arrow) graft, and a right internal mammary artery to LAD artery (straight arrow) graft in a “Y” anastomosis with the left internal mammary artery. <b>(b)</b> Curved planar reconstruction CT image shows complete occlusion of the left internal mammary artery graft (straight arrow) to the ramus intermedius (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic" aria-label="String phenomenon. (a–c) Volume-rendered technique (a) and curved planar reconstruction (b) CTA images in a 59-year-old man show diffuse uniform narrowing of the left internal mammary artery graft (LIMA) (straight arrow) without focal or anastomotic narrowing, which is called the string phenomenon. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image (c) shows that the string phenomenon is due to competitive flow across a stented proximal LAD artery (curved arrow). Also note that the diameter of the distal LAD artery beyond the anastomotic site (*, straight arrow) is larger than the diameter of the left internal mammary artery. (d) Curved planar reconstruction CTA image in a 58-year-old woman shows a normal left internal mammary artery–LAD artery graft with diffusely normal caliber of the graft, the anastomotic site, and the distal LAD artery beyond the graft."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig20a.jpeg" height="1569" width="662" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. String phenomenon. <b>(a–c)</b> Volume-rendered technique <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction <b>(b)</b> CTA images in a 59-year-old man show diffuse uniform narrowing of the left internal mammary artery graft <i>(LIMA)</i> (straight arrow) without focal or anastomotic narrowing, which is called the string phenomenon. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image <b>(c)</b> shows that the string phenomenon is due to competitive flow across a stented proximal LAD artery (curved arrow). Also note that the diameter of the distal LAD artery beyond the anastomotic site (*, straight arrow) is larger than the diameter of the left internal mammary artery. <b>(d)</b> Curved planar reconstruction CTA image in a 58-year-old woman shows a normal left internal mammary artery–LAD artery graft with diffusely normal caliber of the graft, the anastomotic site, and the distal LAD artery beyond the graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic" aria-label="String phenomenon. (a–c) Volume-rendered technique (a) and curved planar reconstruction (b) CTA images in a 59-year-old man show diffuse uniform narrowing of the left internal mammary artery graft (LIMA) (straight arrow) without focal or anastomotic narrowing, which is called the string phenomenon. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image (c) shows that the string phenomenon is due to competitive flow across a stented proximal LAD artery (curved arrow). Also note that the diameter of the distal LAD artery beyond the anastomotic site (*, straight arrow) is larger than the diameter of the left internal mammary artery. (d) Curved planar reconstruction CTA image in a 58-year-old woman shows a normal left internal mammary artery–LAD artery graft with diffusely normal caliber of the graft, the anastomotic site, and the distal LAD artery beyond the graft."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig20b.jpeg" height="1569" width="478" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. String phenomenon. <b>(a–c)</b> Volume-rendered technique <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction <b>(b)</b> CTA images in a 59-year-old man show diffuse uniform narrowing of the left internal mammary artery graft <i>(LIMA)</i> (straight arrow) without focal or anastomotic narrowing, which is called the string phenomenon. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image <b>(c)</b> shows that the string phenomenon is due to competitive flow across a stented proximal LAD artery (curved arrow). Also note that the diameter of the distal LAD artery beyond the anastomotic site (*, straight arrow) is larger than the diameter of the left internal mammary artery. <b>(d)</b> Curved planar reconstruction CTA image in a 58-year-old woman shows a normal left internal mammary artery–LAD artery graft with diffusely normal caliber of the graft, the anastomotic site, and the distal LAD artery beyond the graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic" aria-label="String phenomenon. (a–c) Volume-rendered technique (a) and curved planar reconstruction (b) CTA images in a 59-year-old man show diffuse uniform narrowing of the left internal mammary artery graft (LIMA) (straight arrow) without focal or anastomotic narrowing, which is called the string phenomenon. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image (c) shows that the string phenomenon is due to competitive flow across a stented proximal LAD artery (curved arrow). Also note that the diameter of the distal LAD artery beyond the anastomotic site (*, straight arrow) is larger than the diameter of the left internal mammary artery. (d) Curved planar reconstruction CTA image in a 58-year-old woman shows a normal left internal mammary artery–LAD artery graft with diffusely normal caliber of the graft, the anastomotic site, and the distal LAD artery beyond the graft."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig20c.jpeg" height="1569" width="433" aria-labelledby="fig20c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span>. String phenomenon. <b>(a–c)</b> Volume-rendered technique <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction <b>(b)</b> CTA images in a 59-year-old man show diffuse uniform narrowing of the left internal mammary artery graft <i>(LIMA)</i> (straight arrow) without focal or anastomotic narrowing, which is called the string phenomenon. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image <b>(c)</b> shows that the string phenomenon is due to competitive flow across a stented proximal LAD artery (curved arrow). Also note that the diameter of the distal LAD artery beyond the anastomotic site (*, straight arrow) is larger than the diameter of the left internal mammary artery. <b>(d)</b> Curved planar reconstruction CTA image in a 58-year-old woman shows a normal left internal mammary artery–LAD artery graft with diffusely normal caliber of the graft, the anastomotic site, and the distal LAD artery beyond the graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20d" class="graphic" aria-label="String phenomenon. (a–c) Volume-rendered technique (a) and curved planar reconstruction (b) CTA images in a 59-year-old man show diffuse uniform narrowing of the left internal mammary artery graft (LIMA) (straight arrow) without focal or anastomotic narrowing, which is called the string phenomenon. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image (c) shows that the string phenomenon is due to competitive flow across a stented proximal LAD artery (curved arrow). Also note that the diameter of the distal LAD artery beyond the anastomotic site (*, straight arrow) is larger than the diameter of the left internal mammary artery. (d) Curved planar reconstruction CTA image in a 58-year-old woman shows a normal left internal mammary artery–LAD artery graft with diffusely normal caliber of the graft, the anastomotic site, and the distal LAD artery beyond the graft."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig20d.jpeg" height="1569" width="977" aria-labelledby="fig20d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20d</span>. String phenomenon. <b>(a–c)</b> Volume-rendered technique <b>(a)</b> and curved planar reconstruction <b>(b)</b> CTA images in a 59-year-old man show diffuse uniform narrowing of the left internal mammary artery graft <i>(LIMA)</i> (straight arrow) without focal or anastomotic narrowing, which is called the string phenomenon. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image <b>(c)</b> shows that the string phenomenon is due to competitive flow across a stented proximal LAD artery (curved arrow). Also note that the diameter of the distal LAD artery beyond the anastomotic site (*, straight arrow) is larger than the diameter of the left internal mammary artery. <b>(d)</b> Curved planar reconstruction CTA image in a 58-year-old woman shows a normal left internal mammary artery–LAD artery graft with diffusely normal caliber of the graft, the anastomotic site, and the distal LAD artery beyond the graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig20d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic" aria-label="CABG aneurysm in two patients. (a) Axial CTA image in a 74-year-old man shows a large partially thrombosed venous graft aneurysm (curved arrow) and a proximal graft thrombus that protrudes into the aortic lumen (straight arrow). (b) Axial single-shot fast spin-echo MR image in a 65-year-old man shows a large CABG aneurysm located in the right inferior atrioventricular groove (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig21a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. CABG aneurysm in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CTA image in a 74-year-old man shows a large partially thrombosed venous graft aneurysm (curved arrow) and a proximal graft thrombus that protrudes into the aortic lumen (straight arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial single-shot fast spin-echo MR image in a 65-year-old man shows a large CABG aneurysm located in the right inferior atrioventricular groove (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic" aria-label="CABG aneurysm in two patients. (a) Axial CTA image in a 74-year-old man shows a large partially thrombosed venous graft aneurysm (curved arrow) and a proximal graft thrombus that protrudes into the aortic lumen (straight arrow). (b) Axial single-shot fast spin-echo MR image in a 65-year-old man shows a large CABG aneurysm located in the right inferior atrioventricular groove (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig21b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. CABG aneurysm in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CTA image in a 74-year-old man shows a large partially thrombosed venous graft aneurysm (curved arrow) and a proximal graft thrombus that protrudes into the aortic lumen (straight arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial single-shot fast spin-echo MR image in a 65-year-old man shows a large CABG aneurysm located in the right inferior atrioventricular groove (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic" aria-label="CABG pseudoaneurysm in a 57-year-old man. Sagittal multiplanar CTA image shows a pseudoaneurysm (curved arrow) emanating from the anastomosis between a reversed saphenous venous graft (straight white arrow) and the posterior descending coronary artery. High-attenuation fluid is present in the inferior pericardial space surrounding this pseudoaneurysm, which is consistent with a hemopericardium (black arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig22.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. CABG pseudoaneurysm in a 57-year-old man. Sagittal multiplanar CTA image shows a pseudoaneurysm (curved arrow) emanating from the anastomosis between a reversed saphenous venous graft (straight white arrow) and the posterior descending coronary artery. High-attenuation fluid is present in the inferior pericardial space surrounding this pseudoaneurysm, which is consistent with a hemopericardium (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic" aria-label="Graft dehiscence in a 63-year-old man. Axial CTA image shows focal discontinuity of the proximal anastomosis of the CABG (straight arrow) surrounded by a large collection of fluid (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig23.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Graft dehiscence in a 63-year-old man. Axial CTA image shows focal discontinuity of the proximal anastomosis of the CABG (straight arrow) surrounded by a large collection of fluid (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic" aria-label="Complications of the Bentall procedure in two patients. (a) Sagittal oblique maximum intensity projection CTA image in a 45-year-old man shows aneurysms of the right (straight arrow) and left (curved arrow) coronary artery buttons in a patient who previously underwent the Bentall procedure. Note the mechanical aortic valve and aortic grafts. (b) Axial oblique maximum intensity projection CTA image in a 69-year-old woman after she underwent the Bentall procedure shows a calcified predominantly thrombosed pseudoaneurysm (straight arrow) that originates from the left aortic sinus and involves the ostium of the left main coronary artery (curved arrow). At cardiac catheterization (not shown), only mild narrowing of the left main coronary artery was identified with no hemodynamically significant stenosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig24a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. Complications of the Bentall procedure in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique maximum intensity projection CTA image in a 45-year-old man shows aneurysms of the right (straight arrow) and left (curved arrow) coronary artery buttons in a patient who previously underwent the Bentall procedure. Note the mechanical aortic valve and aortic grafts. <b>(b)</b> Axial oblique maximum intensity projection CTA image in a 69-year-old woman after she underwent the Bentall procedure shows a calcified predominantly thrombosed pseudoaneurysm (straight arrow) that originates from the left aortic sinus and involves the ostium of the left main coronary artery (curved arrow). At cardiac catheterization (not shown), only mild narrowing of the left main coronary artery was identified with no hemodynamically significant stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic" aria-label="Complications of the Bentall procedure in two patients. (a) Sagittal oblique maximum intensity projection CTA image in a 45-year-old man shows aneurysms of the right (straight arrow) and left (curved arrow) coronary artery buttons in a patient who previously underwent the Bentall procedure. Note the mechanical aortic valve and aortic grafts. (b) Axial oblique maximum intensity projection CTA image in a 69-year-old woman after she underwent the Bentall procedure shows a calcified predominantly thrombosed pseudoaneurysm (straight arrow) that originates from the left aortic sinus and involves the ostium of the left main coronary artery (curved arrow). At cardiac catheterization (not shown), only mild narrowing of the left main coronary artery was identified with no hemodynamically significant stenosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig24b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. Complications of the Bentall procedure in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique maximum intensity projection CTA image in a 45-year-old man shows aneurysms of the right (straight arrow) and left (curved arrow) coronary artery buttons in a patient who previously underwent the Bentall procedure. Note the mechanical aortic valve and aortic grafts. <b>(b)</b> Axial oblique maximum intensity projection CTA image in a 69-year-old woman after she underwent the Bentall procedure shows a calcified predominantly thrombosed pseudoaneurysm (straight arrow) that originates from the left aortic sinus and involves the ostium of the left main coronary artery (curved arrow). At cardiac catheterization (not shown), only mild narrowing of the left main coronary artery was identified with no hemodynamically significant stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic" aria-label="Complications of the Cabrol procedure in a 27-year-old woman. (a) Double oblique CTA image after aortic valve replacement and ascending aortic graft repair, including placement of a Cabrol graft (*), shows a patent RCA limb of the Cabrol graft (arrow) with mild intimal thickening. (b) Double oblique CTA image obtained 4 months later shows the nonopacification of the RCA limb of the Cabrol graft (arrow), which is indicative of thrombosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig25a.jpeg" height="1447" width="1447" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span>. Complications of the Cabrol procedure in a 27-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Double oblique CTA image after aortic valve replacement and ascending aortic graft repair, including placement of a Cabrol graft (*), shows a patent RCA limb of the Cabrol graft (arrow) with mild intimal thickening. <b>(b)</b> Double oblique CTA image obtained 4 months later shows the nonopacification of the RCA limb of the Cabrol graft (arrow), which is indicative of thrombosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic" aria-label="Complications of the Cabrol procedure in a 27-year-old woman. (a) Double oblique CTA image after aortic valve replacement and ascending aortic graft repair, including placement of a Cabrol graft (*), shows a patent RCA limb of the Cabrol graft (arrow) with mild intimal thickening. (b) Double oblique CTA image obtained 4 months later shows the nonopacification of the RCA limb of the Cabrol graft (arrow), which is indicative of thrombosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig25b.jpeg" height="1447" width="1204" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span>. Complications of the Cabrol procedure in a 27-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Double oblique CTA image after aortic valve replacement and ascending aortic graft repair, including placement of a Cabrol graft (*), shows a patent RCA limb of the Cabrol graft (arrow) with mild intimal thickening. <b>(b)</b> Double oblique CTA image obtained 4 months later shows the nonopacification of the RCA limb of the Cabrol graft (arrow), which is indicative of thrombosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26a" class="graphic" aria-label="Complications of arterial switch surgery for dextro-transposition of the great arteries (D-TGA) in a 29-year-old man. (a) Axial oblique CTA image shows a single coronary artery originating from the right aortic sinus, with narrowing of the left coronary artery (arrow). (b) Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows subendocardial late gadolinium enhancement (arrow), which is compatible with a nontransmural myocardial infarction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig26a.jpeg" height="1433" width="1383" aria-labelledby="fig26a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26a</span>. Complications of arterial switch surgery for dextro-transposition of the great arteries (D-TGA) in a 29-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique CTA image shows a single coronary artery originating from the right aortic sinus, with narrowing of the left coronary artery (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows subendocardial late gadolinium enhancement (arrow), which is compatible with a nontransmural myocardial infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig26a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26b" class="graphic" aria-label="Complications of arterial switch surgery for dextro-transposition of the great arteries (D-TGA) in a 29-year-old man. (a) Axial oblique CTA image shows a single coronary artery originating from the right aortic sinus, with narrowing of the left coronary artery (arrow). (b) Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows subendocardial late gadolinium enhancement (arrow), which is compatible with a nontransmural myocardial infarction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig26b.jpeg" height="1433" width="1217" aria-labelledby="fig26b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26b</span>. Complications of arterial switch surgery for dextro-transposition of the great arteries (D-TGA) in a 29-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique CTA image shows a single coronary artery originating from the right aortic sinus, with narrowing of the left coronary artery (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows subendocardial late gadolinium enhancement (arrow), which is compatible with a nontransmural myocardial infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig26b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary artery unroofing with residual stenosis. Axial oblique multiplanar CTA image in a 32-year-old woman with an unroofed anomalous RCA shows residual focal stenosis of greater than 50% (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig27.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Coronary artery unroofing with residual stenosis. Axial oblique multiplanar CTA image in a 32-year-old woman with an unroofed anomalous RCA shows residual focal stenosis of greater than 50% (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary artery unroofing with an aneurysm in a 26-year-old man. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image shows a small saccular aneurysm (straight arrow) adjacent to an unroofed RCA (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig28.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig28" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28</span>. Coronary artery unroofing with an aneurysm in a 26-year-old man. Curved planar reconstruction CTA image shows a small saccular aneurysm (straight arrow) adjacent to an unroofed RCA (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig28">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29a" class="graphic" aria-label="Competitive flow with a thrombosed left internal mammary artery graft in a 64-year-old man with a history of an anomalous left coronary artery originating from the right aortic sinus, which was treated with placement of a left internal mammary artery graft to the LAD coronary artery. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the right aortic sinus (arrow), with an intramuscular course. (b) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a completely thrombosed left internal mammary artery graft (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig29a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig29a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29a</span>. Competitive flow with a thrombosed left internal mammary artery graft in a 64-year-old man with a history of an anomalous left coronary artery originating from the right aortic sinus, which was treated with placement of a left internal mammary artery graft to the LAD coronary artery. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the right aortic sinus (arrow), with an intramuscular course. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a completely thrombosed left internal mammary artery graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig29a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29b" class="graphic" aria-label="Competitive flow with a thrombosed left internal mammary artery graft in a 64-year-old man with a history of an anomalous left coronary artery originating from the right aortic sinus, which was treated with placement of a left internal mammary artery graft to the LAD coronary artery. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the right aortic sinus (arrow), with an intramuscular course. (b) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a completely thrombosed left internal mammary artery graft (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig29b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig29b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29b</span>. Competitive flow with a thrombosed left internal mammary artery graft in a 64-year-old man with a history of an anomalous left coronary artery originating from the right aortic sinus, which was treated with placement of a left internal mammary artery graft to the LAD coronary artery. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the right aortic sinus (arrow), with an intramuscular course. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a completely thrombosed left internal mammary artery graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig29b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30a" class="graphic" aria-label="Takeuchi procedure in a 16-year-old adolescent girl. AO = aorta, PA = pulmonary artery. (a) Volume-rendered technique CTA image illustrates the anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the main pulmonary artery (arrow). (b) Curved planar reconstruction CTA image acquired after the Takeuchi procedure was performed shows severe narrowing of the neo–left main coronary artery (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig30a.jpeg" height="1519" width="1131" aria-labelledby="fig30a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30a</span>. Takeuchi procedure in a 16-year-old adolescent girl. <i>AO</i> = aorta, <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered technique CTA image illustrates the anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the main pulmonary artery (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Curved planar reconstruction CTA image acquired after the Takeuchi procedure was performed shows severe narrowing of the neo–left main coronary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig30a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30b" class="graphic" aria-label="Takeuchi procedure in a 16-year-old adolescent girl. AO = aorta, PA = pulmonary artery. (a) Volume-rendered technique CTA image illustrates the anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the main pulmonary artery (arrow). (b) Curved planar reconstruction CTA image acquired after the Takeuchi procedure was performed shows severe narrowing of the neo–left main coronary artery (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig30b.jpeg" height="1519" width="1519" aria-labelledby="fig30b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30b</span>. Takeuchi procedure in a 16-year-old adolescent girl. <i>AO</i> = aorta, <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered technique CTA image illustrates the anomalous origin of the left coronary artery from the main pulmonary artery (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Curved planar reconstruction CTA image acquired after the Takeuchi procedure was performed shows severe narrowing of the neo–left main coronary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig30b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31a" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary aneurysm after performance of the Takeuchi procedure in an 8-year-old boy. Cinematic rendering technique (a) and oblique maximum intensity projection (b) CT images show an aneurysm in the left main coronary artery (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig31a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig31a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31a</span>. Coronary aneurysm after performance of the Takeuchi procedure in an 8-year-old boy. Cinematic rendering technique <b>(a)</b> and oblique maximum intensity projection <b>(b)</b> CT images show an aneurysm in the left main coronary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig31a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31b" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary aneurysm after performance of the Takeuchi procedure in an 8-year-old boy. Cinematic rendering technique (a) and oblique maximum intensity projection (b) CT images show an aneurysm in the left main coronary artery (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig31b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig31b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31b</span>. Coronary aneurysm after performance of the Takeuchi procedure in an 8-year-old boy. Cinematic rendering technique <b>(a)</b> and oblique maximum intensity projection <b>(b)</b> CT images show an aneurysm in the left main coronary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig31b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32a" class="graphic" aria-label="Pseudoaneurysm after performance of the Takeuchi procedure in a 16-year-old adolescent girl. Axial oblique multiplanar CT image (a) and volume-rendered technique CTA image (b) show a large aortic (white straight arrow) and small pulmonary artery (curved arrow) pseudoaneurysm as sequelae of the Takeuchi procedure complicated with mediastinitis (black arrow in a)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig32a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig32a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32a</span>. Pseudoaneurysm after performance of the Takeuchi procedure in a 16-year-old adolescent girl. Axial oblique multiplanar CT image <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered technique CTA image <b>(b)</b> show a large aortic (white straight arrow) and small pulmonary artery (curved arrow) pseudoaneurysm as sequelae of the Takeuchi procedure complicated with mediastinitis (black arrow in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig32a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32b" class="graphic" aria-label="Pseudoaneurysm after performance of the Takeuchi procedure in a 16-year-old adolescent girl. Axial oblique multiplanar CT image (a) and volume-rendered technique CTA image (b) show a large aortic (white straight arrow) and small pulmonary artery (curved arrow) pseudoaneurysm as sequelae of the Takeuchi procedure complicated with mediastinitis (black arrow in a)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200147/asset/images/large/rg.2021200147.fig32b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig32b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32b</span>. Pseudoaneurysm after performance of the Takeuchi procedure in a 16-year-old adolescent girl. Axial oblique multiplanar CT image <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered technique CTA image <b>(b)</b> show a large aortic (white straight arrow) and small pulmonary artery (curved arrow) pseudoaneurysm as sequelae of the Takeuchi procedure complicated with mediastinitis (black arrow in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200147&amp;id=fig32b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><se